{"/service/ndnp/mimtptc/batch_mimtptc_inkster_ver01/data/sn88063294/00340589075/1945090701/1141.xml":{"full_text":"Markets Business\nTNI DETROIT TIMII Friday, Sap*. 7,194 S\n20-C\nWhat\u2019s New\nIn Business\nRetaiiers Protest\nCPA Fr\u2019ce Squeeze\nRx \\RI) S( HR T 7\nRetailers are pretexting that\nthe squeeze OPA h** h#rn ty;hi\nening on the nation's merchants\nto cover up higher costs for\nlabor and raw material*- without\nraising prices to consumers has.\n\u00a3onc about as far as it can go.\nCrux of the argument is the\nOrA s cost absorption theory\nuh ch the storekeepers argue is\nmerely an attempt to make\nthem pay all the Increased cost\nfor encouraging civilian good*\nproduction. In dollars and cents\nfiguro. the merchants bluntly\npoint out mat the> will not have\nsufficient margin left to absorb\nincreased r c>sts for merchand.\nand still let government prire\ncontrollers hold the line at only\nthe consumer lon el.\nThat iu\u00ab the accounting of\nrr>orr than 4b reprcscntatix e\nmerchants from all oxer the\ncountry who reported to Of\u2019A\nlast week in tevpon\u2019-e trv ihe\nprice administrations request\nfor their opinions last month.\n\nShow Score Sheet\nShowing the OTA its own\nore sheet, these retailers docu\nmented that the squeeze started\nback in 1942 when they were\nasked to absorb one general co-t\nincrease. Already in 1945 OPA\nhas allowed 54 general increases\nin costs of merchandise All but\nthree of these the merchant has\nhad to pay out of his own\npocketbook since he must con\ntinue to \u00abell at his wartime\nceilings.\nBesides these general In\ncreases. the retailers continue,\nduring 1915 f'PA has allowed\n3.911 special price adxances for\nindividual manufacturers, proc\nessor*. etc., increases which also\nmust be paid by the nation's\nstorekeepers. Thus far in 1945\nsuch special reliefs already have\ntotaled more than three times\nsimilar advance* in costs during\nthe entire year of 1942.\n\n100-Page Study\nThe rase for the retailer was\nmade public in a 100-page study\nprepared by Dr Jules Packman\nof the New York University\nSchool of Commerce, accounts\nand finance, and Martin R.\nGainsburg. chief economist for\nthe National Industrial Confer\nence Board. These economists\nwere asked to study the effects\nof OPA's cost absorption prin\nciple on the nation's retail in\ndustry by \u2019he OPA Retail\nConversion Pining Committee.\nThis is an informal group of\nmerchants who were individu\nally selected hit month hv the\nconsumer good* price division of\n'T7FA and ir.xited to report their\nopinion*\nIn answer to an oft-repeated\nstatement that lire nation* re\ntail merchant* are making\ngi* ater profit* than ever before,\nthe study points out that 85 per\ncent of retailing s w arji m e\nprofit* have r\u00bb suited directly\nfrom savings in services that\nwartime would not permit them\nto perform for their customers\nhut these are services that re\ntailers arc expected, and already\nhaxc begun to resume.\n\nVeterans' Jobs\nThese are services that will\nprovide many of the job* for re\nturning war veterans and peace\ntime reconversion. Thus most of\ntheir profit margin automati\ncally vxiU cease to exist during\nthis next transition year. The\na\u2019udy also pc.nts out that the\nreported profits, before taxe\u00ab for\nretail corporations was substan\ntially below the wartime earn\nings of all other corporations.\nSuch corporate retail profits\nwere more than a fourth less\nthan those of manufacturing\ncorporations, whose wartime\nearnings increa-e was markedly\naoove the overall coverage.\n0 0 9\nHit 'Ajsumptioni'\nIn summarizing their opinion\nof the rott absorption pnnciple,\nthe authors st^tf:\n\"OPA'a prlre rontrnl program\nfor the transition period re\u00bbt*\nupon a serif* of now arranteri\nassumption*, llrsihlr control\novrr prw-e* of haste coat-of-livlng\nItems might art a* a brake upon\nriiuawav price rises. Hut the\n(Hiliry of rigidly oontrnlllnfr \u00abl\nmnst all price* Hill inipair the\nImentive to produce and thus\nadversely affect the ntimlier of\n)\"h* a* Hell as the supply of\ncivilian goods. A policy of rigid\nprice control while wage in\ncrease* are permitted or encour\nag'd doomed to failure.\"\nSugar Man Promoted\nSAGINAW. Sep* h A. Ree\\ r\nh been to agricultural\nsuper. tsor if the Karmen A Man\ni acturer* Beet S jg*r A\u00abso( latino\nHe sumeeds V .7 Bus* f len. who\nhas irired Great Lake* Sugar Co,\nIV\u2019roit.\nSaum Rejoins Firm I ere\nCia At Saum V S Navv who\n\u00bbh -a apec.gi agent at the Cii\u00bb ngo\noil* r of S\u2019andard Aerident insur\nao< a Co, up* il entering the xerv\nior has be< n riiseharged and y%\nrow associated with the eompany*\nDetroit branrh effire\nDividends\nr\u00ab\u25a0 <t\nra\u00bb P*t#\nlull 4U 4: .1* lA< ,2} \u00bb\u00bbp' .2 s.p 21\nS\u2019ru'Mrt ntilt Cmf .2* 24 *\u00abpt 10\nPlants Speed\nChangeover'\n{EDITOR\u2019S NOTE: Were fa\nanother article on the human\nside of national reconversion by\nBob Considine, INS stat cone-\nI spnndent. who continues his m\ni spection of Detroit.)\nRx 808 CON SI DIN K\n\u201cGranddad hates war. a* you\nknow.\" young Henry Ford 11,\nthe new boss around the huge\nmotor empire, told us as he\ntipped back in his swivel chair.\n\u201cHe was glad to see Willow\nRun finish It* job of making\nB-24*. He is through with Wil\nlow Run now and he'a happy\nabout It. He wants to see us\nand the rest of the Industry get\nbark on the old job.\u2019*\nSo said ihe young Yale man who\nnoxv sits in the office where his\nlate father. Edsel, handled the\nreins. So says most of Detroit.\nDetroit did an incomparable job\nof supplying American fighting\nmen and their Allies xxith the tools\nof victory. N'oxx each hour of its\nday' l- riexoted to the enormous\ntask of changing-over, the prob\nlem of seeing how many of its\n1.35(1.000 war xvorkers it can put\nto work butldtng cars, trucks and\naccessories.\nDETROIT LEADS WORLD\n\u201cThe war taught us very little\nwe didn't already know about\nhulMinf ears.\" a GM .spokesman\nsaid. \u201cIt was the other way\naround: Detroit showed the\nworld how to turn out war sup\nplies a* they\u2019ve nexer been\nturned out before.**\nTalk to any automobile man\nhere and he'll tell you ihat the\nspeed and success of Detroit's\ntraion depend on three\nfactors:\nI\u2014Labor s full ro-oprratinn.\n2 A quick and \u201creasonable\u201d\ndecision by OPA on postwar car\nprices.\n3 Speedy \u201e\u00a3emov a 1 from plants\nof war tools!\"n?tr Reeded by car\nand truck manufacturers.\nEVE COMPETITION\nThe manufacturers are keeping\none eye on the competition, as of\nold\u2014to are that the competition\ndoesn't come out with a new\nshape or engineering improve\nment which would revolutionize\nthe industry.\nDetroil fears a series of test\n\u00abtrikes this coming winter and\nspring, when production is sched\nuled to reach 1941 levels and go\nbeyond. The manufacturer* also\nworry' oxer the Reocvnst rue lion\nFinance Corp.\u2019s delays- in getting\nits old gear out of the way.\nOne think they don't worry\nabout is John Q. Public's apjxetite\nfor a new car.\nAVERAGE CAR BUYER\n\u201cThe public will buy the 194 A\nmodels as fast as the companies\ncan turn them out,\u201d said ex-Maj.\nWaller O. BHggg Jr., whose\nfather makei Chrysler. Packard\nand other bodies. \u201cThe aversfc\near buyer Is a conservative. He\nwants style and changes but ex\nperience show* that he wants\nthewe to be evolutionary, not\nrevolutionary. what hap\npened when the first stream\nlined and front-drive cars were\nplaced on an otherwise conven\ntional market. The public\nwouldn't buy them.*'\nIn the midst of Its reconversion\nprogram, Detroit also is wondering\nif the war, and the war-enforced\nuse of old cars, changed American\ncar drivers.\n\u201cThat\u2019# an Imponderable, hilt\none of the most critical parts of\nreconversion,\u201d J. R. Davis, top\nexecutive in Ford sales, dis\nclosed. \u201cDuring the wnr people\nhad to get along xxith any kind\nof a car, with patchxxork tires\nnod worn-out parts.\nMANGE EVERY 27 MONTHS\nResort Pearl Harbor the ave\narge American motorist turned\nin hi* old car on a new model\nevery 27 months.\n\"Rut during the war men and\nwomen discovered that the auto\nmobile i* a tough old mechan\nism, willing to keep rolling for\ntlioiuanda of inllc* beyond the\npoint where moat people used to\ndrive car*. People learned to\ntake better care of fhelr car*\nduring the war, for they knew\nit hi* Impossible to get a fresh\none.\u201d\nMore urgent concern of Detroit\nis ]fM5 September will bo .slow,\nunemployment will ruse during\ni he month. By October nil but\non\u00ab- or two companies will be\nmaking some cars. November\nwill see tin pace quickened. De\ncember will bring additional pace,\nand so on until April when De\ntroit hopes and prays >as do its\njobless workingmen! that Detroit\nwill be Detroit again\n(\"Tomorrow; Cars of tht fu\nture\nGas Sendout Here\nBelow 1944 Period\nGas v, ndout in the Detroit dll\n\u2019riot {nr the week ended Sept. 1\nwm 40.'f IK* </xj cubic feet, Michi\ngan onso\u2019idateri Gas Co reported\ntoriav a decrease of 3A.093.000\ncub f< c* '-ompared with the cor\nreminding week la\u00abt vear.\nDevelop New Acid Lift\nGeorg* L Nankervi* Co. of De\n*rc\u00bbit ha\u00ab ecentlv completed the\ndevelopment of a new ar id lift for\nuse in the continuous skimming of\na< d dip lank* The new lift ha*\nno moving part* and i\u00ab operated\nh> six i*r>unii of air pressura.\nFirm O.K's\ni\\ew Issue\nNEW YORK. Sept. A Stock\nholders of Allied Stores Corp\nhaxe voted to authorize 300.000\nshares of <IOO par 4 per rent\ncumulative preferred. It is planned\nto is*ue an initial series of 200.000\nshares of th* 1 new preferred to re\nplace the presently outstanding\n195.225 shares ci SIOO j\u00bbar 5 per\ncent preferred.\nThe lower dividend rate on the\nnew stock will effect a saving\nequal to 10 rents a on the\noutstanding 1.817.153 common\nshares. The action will also free\nabout $1,000,000 a year lor the\npurposes of the corporation\nthrough a reduction in sinking\nfund requirements.\nThe new issue will haxe no con\nversion rights. Sinking fund for\nthe new issue will he 2 per cent\nannually of the largest amount\never issued.\nThe company he\u00ab no plan for the\nremaining authorized but unissued\n100.000 shares of 4 per cent pre\nferred.\nPCA Registers\nBonds With SEC\nPHILADELPHIA, Sept. A\u2014\nPennsylvania Central Airlines\nCorp. has registered with the SEC\n$10,000,000 15-ycar convert ihlr\nincome debentures, due Sept. 1,\n1%0. The interest rate and price\nto the public will he supplied by\namendment.\nNet proceeds will he applied to\nthe purchase of additional aircraft\nand other operating facilities ag\ngregating approximately $7,500\n000. The remaainmg $2,500,000\nwould he reserved for general\n'expansion purposes, including pos\nsible extension of routes.\nFanccl 5 .Million\nI In f'onfrad* Here\nPHILADELPHIA. Sept 6- SEC\nhas released additional contract\nterminations* filed hv two listed\ncompanies from Michigan, The\nsummarized reports follow\nHefti'tnint C\u00a94>! I*< I\nEurrka Vacuum U S* 1\nI'niomi'lf'cd Eureka contract! n\u00abt itrrolnaiM\n-anmated at $5.775 000.\nBerk** Gay Furniture 1 1\nUnfilled portion of other B-rkey A Ga> war\ncontract* not terminated 1* SX\u00bb3\nFarmers\u2019 Market\nF SUlT*\u2014Apple*. W\u2019ealthir, No. 1.\n4Vlb bu Cantaloupe No. 1. 13, J\u201d' n\nbu. fearhai, Hale Haven, fancy. IJ JOO\nhu 1 No 1. *3 S 0(( 3 South Haven fancy.\n*X So>\u00ab4 hu No l, 93SO<i*X. P#kr\u00bb. aart\nlett. No 1. IS bu. Clapp Favorite. N<>\nax.aSSO bu Sugar. No 1, $X bu Slumi\nGreengage No. 1 14.4 50 Sradahaw. lano\nA bu No. 1 *4 snub Burbank, fancy.\nbu No 1, *4 \u00bb0\u00ab5. Watermelon*, No. i.\n$3 so _\nVEGETA BI.E rmiS*-CabM|e. 1\n*b\u00absftr tiu f\u2019ollatda. No. 1. 7 oct*Sl. h\u00bb t\nNo. 1. 7Sc r** 1 bu. Muitaid Uteena No. I\n45\u2022 TSr bu. Spinach, No, 1 7 bet# SI bu\nSorrell No 1, i|l l>