e 88'l, un\nchanged- International Telephone\n25%, off Standard Brand*\n.18up V,; Engineers Public\nService 27 unchanged.\nYew York\nStocks\nHigh Low 12 45\nAm Airlines 66 65% KG\nAm Radiator lfy% 16% 16%\nAm Roll Mill 23% 23 23%\nAm Seating 23'* 25% 25*4\nAm Smelting 54% 54% 54*4\nAm Tel Tel 183 38.3% 183%\nAm Toh R 86 85% 86\nAnaconda 33% 33% 33%\nAtchison 88'* 87% 87%\nAviation Corp 8 8 8\nBalt A Ohio 19% 18% 18%\nBendix Avn 55 55 55\nRohn 83% 83% 83%\nBorg Warner 45% 45% 45%\nBriggs 47% 47% 47%\nBudd Mfg 18% 16% 16%\nRudd Wheel 19% 19% 19%\nBurroughs 17 17 17\nCase 41 41 41\nCerro de Pasco 38 58 38\nChes A Ohio xd 51 51 51\nI Com Southern 1 1 1\nCons Vult Air 22% 22%\nCont Motors xd 11% 11% 31 s\nCurtiss-Wright 6% 6% 6%\nDow Chem 140% 110% 140%\nDu Pont 17.3% 17.*% 17.3%\nF.astnin Kodak 182% 182% 182%\nEl Auto Lite 6.3% 63% 6.3%\nErie 15% 15% 15%\nEureka \\d 11% 11% 14%\nFirestone 62% 62% 62%\nFruehauf Tra 54% 54% 54%\niar Wood 10% Ki% 30%\nClen Electric 47% 47% 47%\nGen Motors 72% 72% 72\nGoodrich 65 61 65\nGoodyea r 37 1 i 57 57\nGraham 11% 11 11%\nGrcvhound 25% 23% 25%\nHayes lnd 1.3% 13% 1.3%\nI Hayes Mfg 10% 10% 10%\nHudson Motor 30% 30% 30%\nHupp Motor 6% 6% 6%\n111 Central 33 33 33\nInti Nickel 3414 34 34\nInti Tel A Tel 25% 25% 25%\nKelsey A 28% 28% 28%\nDo B 23% 25% 25%\nKcnnccott .58 .37% .38\nKresge S S 29 H 29% 29%\nL-O-F Glass 6.3 63 63%\nMontg Ward xd 68 6.8 68\nMueller Brass .39 .30 .39\nMurray Corp 17% 17% 17%\nNash Kelv 21% 21 21%\nNat Auto Fih 16% 16 16%\nNat Dairy 32 31% 31%\nNat Steel 75% 75% 73%\nN Y Central 24% 24% 24%\nNo Am Aviatn 26% 25% 26\nOhio Oil 17% 37% 17%\nPackard 7% 7% 7%\nParke-Da vis 32 32 .32%\nPenn R R 37% .37% .37%\nPfeiffer 10% 10% 10%\nRadio 16% 16% 16%\nReo 22% 22% 22%\nRepub Steel 26 25% 25%\nR< vtre 20 19% 19\nSt Jo Lead 44% 44% 41%\nSear* 3.30% 1.30% 330%\nSinclair Oil 15 15% 15\nSocony 16 15% 16\nSouthern Pac 46 45% 45%\nSpark* With 8% 8% 8%\nSperrv Corp .30% 30% 3ft'*\nStd Brand* .38% 38% .38%\nSO of NJ 61% 61% 61%\nStew- Warner 20% 20 20%\nStudehaker 28% 28% 28%\nCnited Aircraft 27% 27% 27%\nL\u2019nitrd C\u2019orp 2% 2% 2%\nU S Rubber 67% 67 67%\nU S Steel 71% 71% 71%\nWest L\u2019nion 'A* 46% 46% 46%\nWestghae Elec 36% 35% 35%\nWhite Mdtor 35 34 31%\nWilly* 23% 23% 23%\nWool worth 46% 46% 46%\nWriglev 77 77 77\nYg Sp A Wire 24% 24% 24%\nA\u2019s Sign \u2019Teen-Ager\nROXHORO, N C Sept 6 TP)\nPitcher Mason W. Bowes. 18,\nLonghurst. has been signed by\nthe Philadelphia Athletics. Bowes\nwill join the big league club in\nthe next few days.\nBlueprints for America\nmmmm\u2014mmmmmammmmmmmmmammmmmammmmmmmmmmmm\nUrges Public Continue\nFight on Inflation\nEDITORS NOTE \u2014Chester Bowles, OPA administrator,\ntoday acts as guest columnist for M. S. Rukeyser, who is on\nvacation. Tomorrow Roy A. Hunt, prasident. Aluminum Com\npany of America, will discuss tbs outlook for light metals.\nBy CHESTER BOWLER\nAdmlnUlratnr. Offtr* of PrVa AdmlatatraM-a\nFor nearly four year*, every one has been working toward\ntotal victory in the greatest conflict the world ha* ever known\nAt the same time we have been guarding agairtst a disastrous\ninflation such as we experienced following World War I. We\nhave been preparing ourselves and the nation for a tremendous\nreconversion from war to peace.\nToday we stand on the reconversion threshold. Millions\nof Americans will now be able to return to peacetime jobs.\n'Thousands of manufacturers are beginning to make commodi\nties which disappeared from the market when the war began.\nMeanwhile, peak employment during these war year* has raised\nliquid assets in this country to more than 320 billion dollar*\nPeople have lots of money. They\u2019re waiting to spend it for\nthings they had to get along without during the war.\n\nPeriod for Sustained Prosperity Seen for U. S.\nThat is the picture as I see it today. I am convinced ihat\nif we handle things right this country can move forward to a\nperiod of sustained prosperity unlike anything the world has\never seen. There will be good paying jobs for everybody. There\nwill he an unlimited market for business and agriculture. And\nthere will be unprecedented peacetime production with excellent\nprofits for manufacturers, for wholesalers and for retailers.\nLike many people, however. I am fearful of how cloaely the\npicture today resembles the situation we saw after the 1918\narmistice. 1 think we could easily fool ourselves Into again ignor\ning these Inflation storm warnings\u2014just as we ignored them alter\nWorld War I. I don't think any of us can look hard enough\nor long enough at what happened before In the first few months\nfollowing the armistice, as industry shifted to peacetime produc\ntion, ihcrc was a short lull and pric* s sagged. What few war\ntime controls existed were trtken off. People seemed to think\nthe danger of inflation was over.\nBut by March. 1919, workers back In peacetime Jobs ru*hrd\nto stores to spend their savings. Reiailers. wholesalers, manufac\nturers began a wild scramble for good*. Prices skyrocketed\n0 0 0\nFrantic Businessmen Canceled Huge Orders\nBy .lime, wages had lagged behind prices, and buying power\ncould not anywhere keep up with demand. Frantic businessmen,\nmanufacturers, began to cancel huge supply orders and dump\ntheir inventories to try and get out from the avalanche that was\nhurtling prices to rock bottom. After the crash we had a dreary\nreckoning. One hundred and six thousand businesses had gone\nbankrupt. Four hundred and fifty three thousand farmers had\nlost their farms. Pay mils were down 44 per cent. And because\nof our economic fumbling, orderly reconversion was delayed for\nmore than two yeais Millions suffered hard\u00abhip and misery.\nI am convinced that the same thing could happen this time\nFull wartime production and employment has created even\ngreater pent up huving power than it did before. Savings, in\nsurance. property holdings are enormous We could lose them\nagain b> what we do or fail to do m the months ahead.\n0 0 0\nNation on Much Firmer Footing Today\n1 do know tha\u00bb, far a\u00ab prices and rent control ate con\ncerned, we air nn a much firmer footing than we were in 1918.\nPrices so far have increased only a fraction of the ri*r between\n191 Land 1920. Wage* and prices are in far better balance.\nMass production and full employment am the answer to in\nflation. Mass market* arc the key. And ma>* markets can he\nachieved only at price* people can afford to pay prices that will\nallow payment of high wages with good profits at norma] produc\ntion levels.\nMeanwhile. T think It Is essential that we relax some of our\npro'-ent war controls a* soon there is no longer any danger\nof their blowing up the inflationary balloon\nSteels Extend\nRate to 76 Pet.\nNEW YORK Sept 5 Steel In\ngot production for the week ended\nSept. 3 is placed at 76 jwr cent\nof capacity in ihe compilation by\nDow- Jones A Co, Inc. This com\nparca with 67 per cent in the\nprevious week and 60 per cent\ntwo week* 'togo.\nU. S steel is estimated at 72\nj**r cent against 6U per cent jn\nthe week before and 50 per cent\ntwo wrek* ago. (>ther leading com\npanies are credited with 78 per\ncent again*t 72 per cent in the\npreceding week and 67 per cent\ntwo weeks ago.\nDetroit Stocks\nNH\nIn loo\u00bb Hi|h l.i'* 12 4* Cn*\nPin t\u00ab t| 1 2 3 3 u\nt\u00bb il* In S 3 J 3 12% 13%\nBro-n-MtL 11 I*, 2-, 1> 1\nP A C Vi 1 S\u2018, .'\u00bbU\ntxt Qiay Ir\u00ab\u00bbii 1 2% 3%\nnnktnniu'.h 20 n 4', 4% 4*.\nGki Wr,od Inc .10 I'\u00bb't to to-,-\nOtn Kln\u00abncf 2> I 10 10% 10%,\nUif* 1* V 4% l% 4%\nUrthtm r\u00abi|\u00ab 2 11% 11% 11-\u00bb,\n40 1 1* Id id....\nHurd L'-c\u00bb is 1 7% 7 7%_\nM4M-n Srodu 10 1* 2 1% 1t*.....\nMK'l4H4h4>' Oil S 70 70 70.,..,\nMlct. Di# C\u00bbm !0 s 3% 3't 3%\n*4nn' 00 4 44%. 4 4,\n*ld TuN Co 0* l 4-* 4 d-,\nfdplt. Corn 10% 10% 10%,\nUnlv'cnol A 37% 17% 17% 17%\nWtrn Aircrill In 3 1% 1% 1%,\nI NI.IITF.D\nN*lh K,l\u00bb 37% J. 31 :i VI\nh Y C\u00bbnf4l l 1 24\u2